3 Visual Predictive Check
The VPC simulates many virtual trials from the fitted model and overlays the observed data on the simulated prediction intervals. If the observed median and spread fall within the simulated bands across time, the model reproduces both the typical profile and the between-subject variability — the key qualification for using it to simulate (Phase 7).


Code
vpc &lt;- make_vpc(fit, n = 500)
if (!is.null(vpc)) {
  vpc
} else {
  cat("VPC requires the 'vpc' package. Install with renv::install('vpc'), then re-render.")
}





Visual Predictive Check: observed data vs model-simulated prediction intervals.

4 Key takeaways

GOF: observed-vs-predicted should track the identity line, tighter for IPRED.
CWRES: a flat, ±2 band with no time/PRED trend indicates the structural and error models are adequate.
VPC: observed percentiles inside the simulated intervals confirm the model captures central tendency and variability.
Passing these checks is what licenses the model for the clinical simulations in the next phase.


Next: Phase 7 — Simulation: use the qualified model to simulate PK profiles for a typical patient and weight-based subgroups.





